(a) Since the country can sell and buy goods on the world market, to achieve the consumption of the largest quantity of good sets, it needs to achieve the highest income from trade. For this, the country needs to use its resources as efficiently as possible. First, let's find the equation of the production possibilities frontier (PPF) of the country.

$Z_{X}+Z_{Y}=100$ according to the problem. At the same time, $Z_{X}=4 X^{2}, Z_{Y}=Y$.

Then the PPF equation is: $4 X^{2}+Y=100$.

The country's income, which uses its resources most efficiently in this case, is $T R=8 X+Y=8 X+100-4 X^{2}$. The maximum of this function, whose graph is a parabola opening downwards, is achieved at a production volume of $X_{\text {prod }}=1, Y_{\text {prod }}=100-4=96$.

The maximum income of the country is then $8 * 1+1 * 96=104$.

Considering the problem's condition, if the country consumes $\mathrm{X}$ units of good X, then it will consume $184 \mathrm{X} / 3$ units of good Y. Since the country will spend 104 monetary units on a set of goods in such a proportion, $8 X_{\text {cons }}+Y_{\text {cons }}=104$, where $Y_{\text {cons }}=184 X_{\text {cons }} / 3$ and the residents of the country will be able to consume $X_{\text {cons }}=1.5$ and $Y_{\text {cons }}=92$.

Let's graphically represent the obtained production and consumption volumes.

