Question 234, Solution: When $n \geq 11$, since $\sqrt[3]{a_{1}}, \sqrt[3]{a_{2}}, \ldots, \sqrt[3]{a_{n}}$ all fall within the interval $[1,10]$, according to the pigeonhole principle, there must exist two numbers $\sqrt[3]{a_{i}}, \sqrt[3]{a_{j}}$ such that $0<\left|\sqrt[3]{a_{i}}-\sqrt[3]{a_{j}}\right|<1$. Therefore,
$$
\begin{array}{l}
0<\left|a_{i}-a_{j}\right|=\left|\left(\sqrt[3]{a_{i}}-\sqrt[3]{a_{j}}\right)^{3}+3\left(\sqrt[3]{a_{i}}-\sqrt[3]{a_{j}}\right) \cdot \sqrt[3]{a_{i} a_{j}}\right| \\
\leq\left|\left(\sqrt[3]{a_{i}}-\sqrt[3]{a_{j}}\right)^{3}\right|+3\left|\left(\sqrt[3]{a_{i}}-\sqrt[3]{a_{j}}\right)\right| \cdot \sqrt[3]{a_{i} a_{j}} \\
<1+3 \sqrt[3]{a_{i} a_{j}}
\end{array}
$$

On the other hand, when $n=10$, take $a_{i}=i^{3}, i=1, 2, \ldots, 10$. Then for any $i \neq j$, we have $\mid a_{i}-a_{j}|=| i^{3}-j^{3}|=| i-j|\cdot|(i-j)^{2}+3 i j \mid \geq 1+3 i j=1+3 \sqrt[3]{a_{i} a_{j}}$, which does not meet the requirement.
In summary, the smallest value of $n$ that satisfies the condition is 11.

